{
  "doc_id": "42857",
  "text": "HSPs are important chaperone proteins that are produced endogenously. HSPs are named according to their molecular weight, such as HSP90, HSP70, HSP60, and small heat-shock proteins. HSPs are induced in response to a variety of stressors, including elevated temperature, hypoxia, inflammation, and ischemia [CITATION_1] . In this study, the expression of HSP27, HSP40, and HSP90 were assessed in the plasma of H1N1 infected patients and the control subjects, and significant increases in HSP27 and HSP90 expression were found in H1N1 infected patients than in the control subjects. HSP27 has a strong protective activity against a number of cytotoxic agents, including heat shock, oxidative stress, chemotherapeutic agents, and cytokines [CITATION_2] . It may also play the role as a potential biomarker of disease and therapeutic target [CITATION_3] . In a proteomic study, HSP27 was found to be upregulated in A549 human lung carcinoma cells infected with an influenza virus [CITATION_4] ). In addition, [CITATION_5] reported that HSP27 enhanced the inhibitory effect of influenza virus NS1 on the expression of interferon beta.",
